### 4.3 Atom-length enforcement (current state)

`text_atoms.text` has a CHECK constraint enforcing length 8–240, no newlines, no fenced code, no pipe-table syntax. The CHECK fires at INSERT time inside the handler's `write_tx`. The 289-char `items[2]` overrun in S133 was caught at INSERT — but the failure surfaced as a SQL CHECK refusal partway through the close-record handler's atom-creation loop, after some atoms had already been created in the transaction (which then rolled back). The Python CLI did not pre-validate.

### 4.4 Analogous handler-level gates (engine history)

- T-27 (engine-v28): refuses `closes_issue` decision-effects with NULL `target_issue_id`. Trigger-level.
- T-28 (engine-v28): refuses any direct `decision_effects` INSERT bypassing `_submit_decision_record` handler dispatch. Trigger-level.
- T-31 (engine-v34): refuses `opens_issue` effects with NULL `target_issue_id`. Trigger-level.

Pattern: the engine has consistently chosen SQL-level triggers for cross-row integrity gates that must hold regardless of which handler writes.

### 4.5 EF-S134-1 (this session's calibration-EF, verbatim)

> S133 closed without a close_record row due to unguarded close-record + session-close sequencing. The close script ran the two submits sequentially without checking close-record return code; close-record refused (atom over 240-char limit on items[2]) and session-close succeeded anyway. Recovery via post-close calibration-EF is itself blocked because engine_feedback requires an open session — a second structural-coupling gap. Operator-named substrate defences: session-close refusing without a prior close_record row; atom-length pre-check at payload deserialisation. S134 opens to ship these as structural feedback loops per constraints property 5.

